[Student "S"]
{North is to play 3NT. East leads the \CA, then \CK, \C2. West follows once, then discards a \S and a \H.

East leads the \CA, then \CK, \C2. West follows once, then discards a \S and a \H.

Winners:   \S=1  \H=3  \D=2  \C=2  Total = 8

There are two possibilities for getting an extra winner. If the \Ds are splitting 3-3 you could play \DA, \DK and another \D and establish the thirteenth \D as a winner. Or you could play West for the \SK and lead toward your \SQ.

The chance of West holding the \SK is a little greater than 50%. (it is higher than the usual 50% because we know he started with only one \C, giving him more spaces for other cards).

The chance of \Ds splitting 3-3 is about 40%.

So you should enter dummy with a \H and play a small \S toward your \SQ.

Did it work?  

You might have thought of another possibility; duck a \D, then play \DA and \DK to see if the \Ds split before you try leading toward the \SQ.

The problem is that you might run into this very distribution. You would establish a \D for West and when you played a \S from dummy West would jump up with the \SK and cash his winning \D for down 1.}
[Play "W"]CA

